{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_iceworm_ver02/data/2018270506/0027952696A/1908060101/0042.xml":{"full_text":"NOME BANK TRUST CO,\nIn September, 190G, the Nome Bank\nTrust Co., with a paid-up capital of\n$135,000, began doing a general bank\ning business, which has since increased\nuntil now it ranks as one of the largest\nfinancial institutions north of Puget\nSound.\nIt was incorporated by men who have\npractically made their fortunes in Alas\nka, and as the shareholders are mostly\nNome people it is a purely local bank,\nand one which this district might well\nfeel proud of.\nAlthough the financial panic that oc\ncurred in the States last fall more or\nless affected business in Alaska, this\ninstitution has continued to increase\ntheir volume of business, which is now\ndouble what it was a year ago.\nA modern and up-to-date assay office\nis conducted in connection with the\nbank, where gold dust is melted and\nassayed, and during the summer sea\nsons this is a busy department. Last\nseason their shipments of bullion\namounted to over two and one-haif\nmillions of dollars, and there is every\nindication that they will handle as\nmuch, if not more, this year.\nThe Nome Bank Trust Company\u2019s\nbuilding at the corner of Lane\u2019s Way\nand Front street is without doubt the\nmost substantial as well as the pret\ntiest structure in Alaska. It is cov\nered inside and out with beautifully de\nsigned pressed steel, is steam heated\nand electric lighted throughout, which\nmakes it as near fire proof as a build\nmg1 can possibly be made in this coun\ntry. The banking room is large and\ncommodious, irichly furnished, with\nplenty of room, and every convenience\nfcr its customers.\nThe president of the bank is Dr. J.\nDennis Arnold, who is also president\nof the Wild Goose Mining Trading\nCo. Dr. Arnold has been prominently\nidentified with the mining industry of\nSeward Peninsula since gold was first\ndiscovered at Nome.\nThe vice president, R. D. Adams, is\no::e of the best known mining men in\nthe district. He has a host of friends\nthroughout Alaska, is an energetic and\nsuccessful miner, having worked sev\neral mines along the \u201cThird Beach\u2019\u2019\nand on Dexter Hill. Through his per\nseverance in prospecting, coupled with\ngood management after locating pay\nho has gathered together a well-de\nserved fortune.\nThe manager, A. E. Todd, is a pi\noneer Alaskan, being one of the first\ndozen men to come over White Pass in\n\u201997. He is acquainted with all the old\ntimers from Skagway to Nome, and\nenjoys the confidence and esteem of all\nwho know him. He assumed the man\nagement of the bank in October last,\nand since that time the business of the\nbank has developed to aun extent most\ngratifying to the directors and share\nholders. With Mr. Todd as manager\nthe patrons of the bank are sure to re\nceive courteous treatment as well as\nconfidence in the matter of their ac\ncounts and affairs in general.\n\nWe regard the Nome Bank Trust\nCo. as one of our strongest institutions,\nand bespeak for it a long continuance\nof its present prosperity.\nENGINEERS COME TO CUT\nST. MICHAEL CANAL.\nA corps of engineers came north on\nthe steamship Northwestern for the\npurpose of digging the great canal at\nSt. Michael, for which the government\nhas made a special appropriation.\nMr. Wheeler, who is in charge of the\ngreat undertaking, has six men with\nhim in addition to the corps of engi\nneers, and 16 men more are accom\npanying the big dredge which is com\ning north in tow of the steamer Hva\ndes. All the other men will probably\nbe hired in this city.\nThe immensity of the work to be ac\ncomplished can be judged by the fact\nthat a quarter million dollars will be\nexpended this year. That amount has\nbeen specially appropriated for the\npresent year, and further appropria\ntions will be made as the work pro\nceeds and the circumstances demand.\nThe canal will cut off the elbows ot\nthe natural canal which leads from the\nmouth of the Yukon to the fort and\nwai chouses of the companies, and\nwhich is well known to those who have\ncome down the river.\nMr. Wheeler is one of the leading en\ngineers of the country and has been\nentrusted with the accomplishment of\nthe work because of the great ability\nshown by him in work of a similar na\nture.\nThe completion of the undertaking\nwill require the expenditure of a much\ngreater sum than that already appro\npriated.\nCAPITAL INTERESTED IN PLAN\nTO BRING WATER TO COF\nFEE CREEK.\nAmong those who came north Witr.\nGriff Yarnell are experts who were sent\nto investigate the conditions which\nsurround Coffee creek with a view to\nascertaining the expediency of bring\ning water to that stream from the\nSawtooth range.\nThe idea is to use 17 miles of piping\nand to take the water from a place\nwhich will give the immense amount of\n500 feet pressure at the outlet.\nThe investigation will begin at once,\nand the real work will not be delayed\nshould conditions prove favorable, as\nthe amount of capital interested is\npractically unlimited.","height":"28824","width":"21676"}}
